import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# some convenient labels
INFLUENTIAL = 1
FOLLOWER = 2
STUBBORN = 3
In [2]:
def get_payoff(A, B, R, x_0, T, delta): 
    Q = (1/x_0.size) * np.identity(x_0.size)
    K_t = Q
    K_sequence = [Q]
    for i in range(T):
        K_t = delta * A.T @ (K_t - K_t @ B @ np.linalg.inv(B.T @ K_t @ B + R / delta) @ B.T @ K_t) @ A + Q
        K_sequence.insert(0, K_t)

    x_t = x_0
    r_ts = []
    payoff = 0
    payoffs = []
    x_ts = [x_0]
    i = 0
    for K in K_sequence[1:]:
        L = -(np.linalg.inv(B.T @ K @ B + R / delta) @ B.T @ K @ A)
        r_t = L @ x_t
        r_ts.append(r_t.item())
        payoff += (-1 * delta**i * (x_t.T @ Q @ x_t)).item() + (-1 * delta**i * (R * r_t**2)).item()
        payoffs.append(payoff)
        x_t_new = A @ x_t + B @ r_t
        x_ts.append(x_t_new)
        x_t = x_t_new
        i += 1
        
    return payoff, payoffs, r_ts, K_sequence, x_ts
In [3]:
from io import BytesIO
from PIL import Image
from IPython.display import HTML
from base64 import b64encode

def solve(target, delta = 1, x_0 = np.array([[-10], [7], [20]], ndmin = 2)):
    T = 30
    R = 0
    b = 0.1 # the influence weight
    A = np.array([
      [a * [1.0, 1.0-b][target == INFLUENTIAL] for a in A_nobody[0]], # influential agent
      [a * [1.0, 1.0-b][target == FOLLOWER] for a in A_nobody[1]], # follower agent
      [a * [1.0, 1.0-b][target == STUBBORN] for a in A_nobody[2]], # stubborn agent
    ], ndmin = 2)
    B = np.array([
      [[0.0, b][target == INFLUENTIAL]],
      [[0.0, b][target == FOLLOWER]],
      [[0.0, b][target == STUBBORN]],
    ], ndmin = 2)
    return get_payoff(A, B, R, x_0, T, delta)

Test with $\delta = 0.8$¶

In [4]:
images = []
for aii in np.linspace(0.7, 0.999, 30):
    A_nobody = [
        [0.8, 0.2, 0.0],
        [0.5, 0.5, 0.0],
        [1 - aii, 0.0, aii]
    ]
    for agent in ["INFLUENTIAL", "FOLLOWER"]:
        payoff, payoffs, _, _, _ = solve(globals()[agent], delta = 0.8)
        plt.plot(range(25), payoffs[5:], label = "target " + agent.lower() + " agent")
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel("time")
    plt.ylabel("cumulative payoff")
    plt.title("delta = 0.8, self-weight " + str(aii))
    filex = BytesIO()
    plt.savefig(filex, format = "png", facecolor= (1, 1, 1))
    plt.clf()
    plt.close()
    filex.seek(0)
    images.append(filex)

# graphical engine reused from 
# https://github.com/jbrightuniverse/Generalized-Price-of-Anarchy/blob/main/Generalized%20Price%20of%20Anarchy.ipynb
imgs = [Image.open(image) for image in images]

masterfilex = BytesIO()
imgs[0].save(fp=masterfilex, format='GIF', append_images=imgs[1:], save_all=True, duration=200, loop=0)
HTML("<img src='data:image/gif;base64,{0}'/>".format(b64encode(masterfilex.getvalue()).decode('utf-8')))

-86.53914734685634 without agent 3; vs with agent 3: -408.995675163008

From this, it would appear that the crossover in the payoff plot occurs due to the weight of the stubborn agent's opinions being much heavier when targeting the influential agent, even though the weight of the other two agents is lesser when targeting the influential agent.

In [21]:
0.84 * x_1_agent3 + 0.16 * -2.89
Out[21]:
12.3056

From here we can see the reason for the slower convergence of agent 3 in the influential case: the magnitude of the opinion of agent 1 is greater when targeting the follower agent because it is more extreme to begin with. Since it converges slower, it stays more negative for longer, and thus allows agent 3 to converge faster.
